{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:19:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18431"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18431"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.68,0.12,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74570"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18431"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8410"},{"type":"tags","id":"10275"},{"type":"tags","id":"10276"},{"type":"tags","id":"10277"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25835"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25837"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74570"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following groups is most likely to have a proportion of Type II muscle fibres that is 60% or higher?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Power athletes and endurance athletes","Power athletes","Endurance athletes","Endurance athletes and non-athletes","Power athletes and non-athletes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMuscle fibres can be classified into two main types: Type I (slow-twitch) and Type II (fast-twitch). These fibres differ in their contraction speed, fatigue resistance, and metabolic properties. \u003Cstrong\u003EPower athletes\u003C/strong\u003E are most likely to have a proportion of Type II muscle fibres that is 60% or higher. These fast-twitch fibres are adapted for quick, powerful movements and are prevalent in athletes who engage in activities requiring bursts of strength and speed, such as sprinting and weightlifting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPower athletes and endurance athletes\u003C/strong\u003E - Endurance athletes typically have a higher proportion of Type I fibres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndurance athletes\u003C/strong\u003E - These athletes have more Type I fibres, which are slow-twitch and fatigue-resistant\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndurance athletes and non-athletes\u003C/strong\u003E - Both groups generally have a lower proportion of Type II fibres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPower athletes and non-athletes\u003C/strong\u003E - Non-athletes do not typically have a high proportion of Type II fibres\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type II muscle fibres, also known as fast-twitch fibres, are more prevalent in power athletes due to their ability to generate quick and forceful contractions.","Power athletes, such as sprinters and weightlifters, typically have a higher proportion of Type II muscle fibres compared to endurance athletes.","Endurance athletes, like marathon runners, have a higher proportion of Type I muscle fibres, which are slow-twitch and more resistant to fatigue."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Longo, U. G., \u0026 Denaro, V. (Eds.). (2023). Textbook of musculoskeletal disorders. Springer Nature","Hughes, S. H. (2022). The Musculoskeletal System: The Musculoskeletal System-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Frontera WR, Ochala J. Skeletal muscle: a brief review of structure and function. Calcif Tissue Int. 2015 Mar;96(3):183-95. doi: 10.1007/s00223-014-9915-y. Epub 2014 Oct 8. PMID: 25294644","Morrison BM. Neuromuscular Diseases. Semin Neurol. 2016 Oct;36(5):409-418. doi: 10.1055/s-0036-1586263. Epub 2016 Sep 23. PMID: 27704495"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18431"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-25T06:20:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-25T06:21:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11149"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74570"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagG